(Advanced) Quest 8 - Car Borrowing DApp Capstone Project (Backend)
Introduction
In this quest as well as the next quest, we’ll be taking all the skills we’ve learnt in all the previous quests and culminating that into a single project. In particular, we’ll be building a Car Borrowing DApp! This DApp will incorporate all functionalities offered by the Hedera Network Services, so we’ll be able to see how each of these services work together in the context of a DApp. 
We’ll also be exploring how we can use a popular wallet, MetaMask, in the context of developing in Hedera. This quest will focus largely on building the backend of the project whereas the subsequent quest will be on building the frontend. 

Ready? Let’s go!

For queries on this quest, join our Discord, head to the #hedera-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.
Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to:
  • Create fungible token and NFT collections using a Solidity smart contract
  • Mint NFTs using a Solidity smart contract
  • Transfer fungible tokens and NFTs using a Solidity smart contract
  • Integrate your MetaMask wallet with Hedera testnet
  • Deploy and interact with smart contracts on Hedera testnet

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Overview of Project
Let’s start by understanding what this project is about. We’ll be building a Car Borrowing Dapp that facilitates the borrowing of cars between a merchant and his customers. This Dapp will utilise all the functionalities offered by the Hedera Network Services we’ve learnt in the previous quests. Now let’s see how this Dapp works!
The Set Up

The merchant starts off by creating an NFT collection (CAR). This NFT collection will represent his fleet of cars that are available to be borrowed. For every car that he adds to his fleet, he’ll mint a new NFT. In other words, every car is represented by 1 NFT. We’ll be using the Hedera Smart Contract Service (HSCS) and Hedera Token Service (HTS) to create and mint NFTs. In addition, every activity that happens in this DApp will be logged as a message in a Topic that we’ll be creating using the Hedera Consensus Service (HCS).

Borrowing A Car

When the customer borrows a car, an NFT is transferred from the merchant to the customer; this mirrors the transferring of the physical car from the merchant to the customer. In return, the customer will have to lock up 1000 HBAR into an escrow smart contract for the duration of the car borrowing. This is to discourage bad behavior from the customer, e.g. doing anything that might damage the vehicle, returning the car late, etc. We’ll be using the HSCS for the escrow functionality. Similar to before, all our activities will be logged as messages to a Topic using the HCS.

Returning A Car

At the end of the borrowing period, the NFT is transferred from the customer back to the merchant. The 1000 HBAR that was locked up in the escrow smart contract is now released back to the customer. After inspecting the returned car, the merchant will award up to 5 Reputation Tokens (REP) to the customer; 0 representing the worst possible customer and 5 presenting a great lending experience (e.g. no scratches, no delays, etc.). We’ll be using the HSCS and HTS to create this fungible token. Same as before, all activities will be logged as messages to a Topic using the HCS.

Now that we have a clearer picture of what this project entails, let’s get started!
Step 2: Intializing the Smart Contract
Most of our functionalities will be contained within a Solidity smart contract, let’s start by creating that first. Same as in Quest 4 and Quest 6, we’ll be using the Remix Online IDE to write our smart contract. 
Head to Remix Online IDE and create a new file titled stackup-hedera-capstone.sol in the contracts folder. Once you’ve done so, copy the code below and paste it into the file you just created.

// SPDX-License-Identifier: GPL-3.0 pragma solidity >=0.7.0 <0.8.9; import "https://github.com/hashgraph/hedera-smart-contracts/blob/v0.2.0/contracts/hts-precompile/HederaResponseCodes.sol"; import "https://github.com/hashgraph/hedera-smart-contracts/blob/v0.2.0/contracts/hts-precompile/IHederaTokenService.sol"; import "https://github.com/hashgraph/hedera-smart-contracts/blob/v0.2.0/contracts/hts-precompile/HederaTokenService.sol"; import "https://github.com/hashgraph/hedera-smart-contracts/blob/v0.2.0/contracts/hts-precompile/ExpiryHelper.sol"; contract MerchantBackend is ExpiryHelper {   event CreatedToken(address tokenAddress);   event MintedToken(int64[] serialNumbers);   event Response(int response);   address public ftAddress;   address public owner;   uint256 public lockupAmount = 100000000000; }

Let’s break down what we just added in!

Similar to what we did in Quest 6 when we created an NFT collection using a Solidity smart contract, we’ll import four smart contracts that are provided by Hedera. These are precompiled smart contracts that expose native Hedera services functionalities. They offer functionalities that we’ll be using in the functions that we’ll be adding to our smart contract in the subsequent steps.

In our smart contract, we define three event. Events are the same as events in other programming languages. Essentially, they are used to inform the calling application about certain states of the smart contract. In our case, we’ll be using events to broadcast four situations - creating a token, minting a token, borrowing/returning responses and giving REP tokens to the customer. We’ll be using them in the functions we create later on.

We also define three variables - ftAddress, owner and lockupAmount:
  • ftAddress - the address of our fungible token collection (will be created later on)
  • owner - the address of the account used to deploy this smart contract
  • lockupAmount - the amount that a customer is required to lock up for the duration of the lending

For our project, we’ll be setting the lockup amount to be 1000 HBAR. You might be wondering - why is the value assigned to lockupAmount 100000000000? Well that’s because the value you see here is in TINYBAR, which if you recall, is 10-8 the size of a HBAR. Therefore, by giving it the value of 100000000000 TINYBAR, we’re equivalently assigning it the value of 1000 HBAR.
Step 3: Creating the Fungible Token Collection
Now we’ll be creating the fungible token collection, Reputation Tokens (REP). We’ll be doing so in the constructor function. Recall that a constructor function is a special type of function that only runs once at the point of contract deployment. 
Copy the code below and paste it into your smart contract. Refer to the code in ‘Working code’ for a reference if you are unsure of where to place the code. The Remix IDE has a convenient code formatter feature that you can use to format your code. Simply right-click anywhere on the smart contract and press on ‘Format Code’. Feel free to use this feature each time after you add more code in the subsequent steps.

constructor() payable {   IHederaTokenService.HederaToken memory token;   token.name = "Reputation Tokens";   token.symbol = "REP";   token.memo = "REP Tokens By: INSERT-STACKUP-NAME";   token.treasury = address(this);   token.expiry = createAutoRenewExpiry(address(this), 7000000);   (int responseCode, address tokenAddress) = HederaTokenService     .createFungibleToken(token, 1000, 0);   if (responseCode != HederaResponseCodes.SUCCESS) {     revert();   }   ftAddress = tokenAddress;   owner = msg.sender;   emit CreatedToken(tokenAddress); }

Here, we’re using the HederaToken and createFungibleToken functions of the helper smart contracts that we imported to create a fungible token. We configure some of its properties such as giving it the name of “Reputation Tokens” and symbol of “REP”. Replace INSERT-STACKUP-NAME in token.memo with your StackUp username.

After creating the token, we save the token address in the variable ftAddress and we also save the address of the account deploying the contract in the variable owner. Both of these variables were intialised in the previous step. Lastly, we emit the CreatedToken event, passing in the token address.
Working code
Step 4: Creating the NFT Collection
Now let’s add in the function to create our NFT collection, Car (CAR). Copy the code below and paste it into your smart contract. Refer to the code in ‘Working code’ for a reference if you are unsure of where to place the code.
function createNFT(string memory name, string memory symbol) external payable {   IHederaTokenService.TokenKey[]     memory keys = new IHederaTokenService.TokenKey[](1);   // Set this contract as supply   keys[0] = getSingleKey(     KeyType.SUPPLY,     KeyValueType.CONTRACT_ID,     address(this)   );   IHederaTokenService.HederaToken memory token;   token.name = name;   token.symbol = symbol;   token.memo = "CAR Collection By: INSERT-STACKUP-NAME";   token.treasury = address(this);   token.tokenSupplyType = true; // set supply to FINITE   token.maxSupply = 10;   token.tokenKeys = keys;   token.freezeDefault = false;   token.expiry = createAutoRenewExpiry(address(this), 7000000);   (int responseCode, address createdToken) = HederaTokenService     .createNonFungibleToken(token);   if (responseCode != HederaResponseCodes.SUCCESS) {     revert("Failed to create non-fungible token");   }   emit CreatedToken(createdToken); }

Here, we’ll be using the HederaToken and createNonFungibleToken functions of our imported helper smart contracts to create our NFT collection. Same as before, replace INSERT-STACKUP-NAME in token.memo with your StackUp username. After creating the NFT collection, we’ll emit the CreatedToken event so that we can broadcast the address of our NFT collection.
Working code
Step 5: Minting an NFT
Recall that for each car that the merchant wants to add to his fleet, he’ll need to mint an NFT. This is because 1 NFT represents 1 car. We already added the function to allow the merchant to create an NFT collection in the previous step. Now let’s add the function to allow the merchant to mint NFTs within the collection!
Copy the code below and paste it into your smart contract. Refer to the code in ‘Working code’ for a reference if you are unsure of where to place the code.

function mintNFT(address token, bytes[] memory metadata) external {   (int response, , int64[] memory serial) = HederaTokenService.mintToken(     token,     0,     metadata   );   if (response != HederaResponseCodes.SUCCESS) {     revert("Failed to mint non-fungible token");   }   emit MintedToken(serial); }

In this function, we’ll be calling the mintToken function of the HederaTokenService helper contract we imported. We’ll be passing in the token address and the CID link to the metadata JSON file that stores the information regarding the NFT we’ll be minting. After the NFT has been minted, we emit the MintedToken event.
Working code
Step 6: Borrowing a Car
Now let’s create the function that will handle the logic behind what happens when a customer borrows a car. Copy the code below and paste it into your smart contract. Refer to the code in ‘Working code’ for a reference if you are unsure of where to place the code.
function borrowing(address nftAddress, int64 serial) external payable {     // Check if customer transfers the lockup amount     require(msg.value == lockupAmount, "Incorrect amount");     // Transfer NFT to customer     int response = HederaTokenService.transferNFT(       nftAddress,       address(this),       msg.sender,       serial     );     if (response != HederaResponseCodes.SUCCESS) {       revert("Failed to transfer non-fungible token");     }     emit Response(response);   }

This function takes in two parameters - the address of the NFT collection and a serial number. This serial number refers to the specific NFT that the customer intends to borrow (i.e. the car that the customer wants to borrow). The first thing we do in the function is to use a require statement to check if the customer transfers the correct amount specified for the lockup (i.e. 1000 HBAR). 

We then proceed to transfer the specified NFT to the customer using HederaTokenService.transferNFT. Lastly, we emit the Response event. The attentive learner will notice that we have yet to associate the NFT to the customer’s account - not to worry, we’ll be doing the token association using the EthersJs library in Quest 9 before this function is called.
Working code
Step 7: Returning a Car
Now let’s create the function that allows customers to return the cars they’ve borrowed. Copy the code below and paste it into your smart contract. Refer to the code in ‘Working code’ for a reference if you are unsure of where to place the code.
function returning(address nftAddress, int64 serial) external payable {     // Return NFT from customer     int response = HederaTokenService.transferNFT(       nftAddress,       msg.sender,       address(this),       serial     );     if (response != HederaResponseCodes.SUCCESS) {       revert("Failed to transfer non-fungible token");     }     // Return HBAR to customer     payable(msg.sender).transfer(lockupAmount);     emit Response(response);   }

The function parameters are the same as the borrowing() function - the address of the NFT and a serial number. 

The serial number refers to the specific NFT that the customer intends to return. In the function, we’ll transfer the NFT from the customer back to the merchant using HederaTokenService.transferNFT. Note that there is no need to associate the merchant account with the NFT since the merchant was the one that created the NFT collection.

We’ll also be releasing the locked up amount (1000 HBAR) from the smart contract back to the customer using .transfer(). Same as the borrowing() function, we’ll emit a Response event.
Working code
Step 8: Giving Reputation Tokens
Recall that after a customer has returned the car, the merchant can allocate up to 5 reputation tokens to the customer, depending on how he felt the lending experience went (5 signifying a good lending experience, and 0 representing a poor lending experience). Let’s create this function!
Copy the code below and paste it into your smart contract. Refer to the code in ‘Working code’ for a reference if you are unsure of where to place the code.

function scoring(address receiver, int64 amount) external {     require(msg.sender == owner, "Not owner");     require(amount <= 5, "Only can allocate up to 5 REP tokens");     int response = HederaTokenService.transferToken(       ftAddress,       address(this),       receiver,       amount     );     if (response != HederaResponseCodes.SUCCESS) {       revert("Transfer Failed");     }     emit Response(response);   }

The function takes as input two parameters - the customer’s address and the amount of reputation tokens to give to the customer. The function first goes through two require checks, the first checks if the person invoking the function is the owner and the second checks that the amount argument given is less than or equal to 5.

After these two checks have been passed, we can proceed to transfer the REP tokens from the merchant to the customer. After transferring the tokens, we emit the Response event.

And we’re done with our smart contract!
Working code

Step 10: Adding Hedera Network To MetaMask
MetaMask is one the most widely used Web3 wallets today. It is a browser extension and mobile app hot wallet that can be used to interact with decentralized apps (Dapps) on Ethereum, EVM-compatible blockchains, and other blockchain networks. MetaMask supports thousands of token transfers across all its supported networks.
With the release of Hedera’s JSON-RPC relay, commonly used Ethereum tools such as Ethers.js and Hardhat can be used when developing on Hedera. Along with the release, MetaMask is now enabled on Hedera too! In this capstone project, we’ll be seeing how we can use MetaMask (instead of HashPack) as our browser wallet to interact with our DApp.

First, we’ll need to make sure that we have MetaMask installed on our browser. If you don’t have MetaMask installed, refer to this guide for a tutorial on how to set up your MetaMask wallet. Ensure that you have your MetaMask wallet set up before proceeding with this step.

To connect to the Hedera testnet, we’ll first need to manually add it as a new network to our MetaMask. Follow the instructions below to do so:
  1. Open up your MetaMask extension and sign in. Then, press on the network drop-down button at the top
  2. Scroll to the bottom of the list and press on ‘Add network’, a new browser window should open up. Press on ‘Add a network manually’
  3. Then, fill in the respective fields accordingly:
    • Network name - Hedera Testnet
    • New RPC URL - https://hashgraph.arkhia.io/hedera/testnet/json-rpc/v1/nT1M9788al140405M1A284I1379To1N5
    • Chain ID - 296
    • Currency symbol - HBAR
  4. Once you’re done filling up the fields, press on ‘Save’. You should get an output similar to ‘Expected output’ after you’re done

NOTE: If you encounter issues connecting your MetaMask wallet to the Hedera testnet, you have the following options:
  1. Use a different browser wallet - Instead of using the MetaMask wallet, you can use another wallet (must be EVM compatible)
  2. Downgrade your MetaMask wallet version - Follow the steps listed in this guide and download version 10.29.0 from Github here. Note that by using this option, you will lose your settings and imported accounts, so be sure to save the necessary settings/accounts before you proceed!
Expected output
Step 11: Importing Hedera Developer Portal Account Into MetaMask
Now that the Hedera Network has been added to our MetaMask, the next thing we’ll need to do is to import our Hedera Developer Portal account into our MetaMask. Recall that we need HBAR to pay for transaction fees in the network. None of your existing accounts in your MetaMask would currently have any testnet HBAR tokens, therefore we’ll need to import our Hedera Developer Portal account since that account contains 10,000 HBAR.
This time round, instead of using the ED25519 account as we’ve been doing for the campaign so far, we’ll be using the ECDSA account instead. The reason why we’ll need to use the ECDSA account information as opposed to ED25519 account information is because ED25519 is a newer type of cryptographic algorithm which is not yet supported by MetaMask. The ECDSA algorithm, on the other hand, is an older algorithm which is supported by MetaMask. 


To import our Hedera Developer Portal account into MetaMask, we’ll need to copy the ECDSA HEX Encoded Private Key. Double check to make sure you’re copying the correct one or else it won’t be able to import into MetaMask! 

Then, open up your MetaMask extension again. Press on your account icon (top right-hand corner) and press on ‘Import account’. Then, paste in your HEX encoded private key and press on ‘Import’. After doing so, you should see a newly imported account in your MetaMask with a balance of 10000 HBAR. Note: it might take up to a few minutes before the 10000 HBAR balance gets updated on your MetaMask, so don’t worry if you don’t see the balance reflected immediately.

While we’re here, let’s go ahead and rename this account to Merchant. To change the name of your account, expand the toggle beside where your account name is, press on the three vertical dots beside your account name -> ‘Account details’ -> pencil icon. As the name suggests, we’ll be using this account to play the role of our merchant in our project.

When all is done, your MetaMask extension should look similar to the image in ‘Expected output’.
Expected output
Step 12: Connecting Our MetaMask Account To Remix
With our MetaMask network and account set up, we’re finally ready to deploy our smart contract to the Hedera testnet! Well, almost. We’ll need to connect our MetaMask wallet to Remix first. Open up your Remix Online IDE again and navigate to the ‘Deploy & run transactions’ menu (Ethereum icon) in the left-hand dashboard menu.


In the ‘ENVIRONMENT’ dropdown menu, select Injected Provider - MetaMask and it should prompt a list of MetaMask accounts to select to allow connection (refer to image above). Select the Merchant account. 



If you do not get a popup after selecting ‘Injected Provider - MetaMask’, then you might need to manually connect your account to Remix. To do so, open up your MetaMask extension and press on the globe icon (refer to image above). Then, press on the ‘connect’ button below your Merchant account.



After you’ve connected your account to Remix, your Merchant account’s wallet address should be displayed under ‘ACCOUNT’, with a balance of 10000 ether (refer to image above). Note that ‘ether’ should be HBAR instead, but the REMIX UI hardcodes the currency displayed to ether.﻿
Step 13: Deploying Our Smart Contract
We’ll need to compile our smart contract before we can deploy it. By default, Remix should have the ‘Auto compile’ feature toggled on. Thus if you look under your workspace repository in Remix, you should see a folder called artifacts. Open it and you should see a file titled MerchantBackend.json. 
Troubleshooting: If you don’t see the artifacts folder, open the ‘SOLIDITY COMPILER’ tab by pressing on the compile icon in the left-hand dashboard menu and tick the ‘Auto compile’ checkbox. The smart contract will compile and you should be able to see the artifacts folder as well as MerchantBackend.json inside it. Don’t worry if you see some warning errors, these should not affect the compiling process.

Now we’re truly ready to deploy our smart contract to the Hedera testnet! Before deploying the smart contract, we’ll need to change the value selected to 20 Ether. Also, make sure that MerchantBackend - contracts/stackup-hedera-capstone.sol is selected under the ‘CONTRACT’ field. Refer to the image below.



Recall in our constructor function, we’re creating a new fungible token collection (REP). Therefore we’ll need to include some HBAR in our contract deployment transaction to pay for the HederaTokenService.createFungibleToken service. Also check that you’ve replaced the two memo values (around line 22 and line 52) with your StackUp username! 

When submitting a transaction in MetaMask, it's important to wait for the gas fees to load from the RPC URL before confirming the transaction on your MetaMask wallet. This is because gas fees are required to execute transactions on the network; and if the gas fee hasn't been loaded yet, the transaction may fail or remain pending. This step of waiting for gas fees to load is good practice for all wallets. We’ll wait till the estimated gas fees appear (refer to image below).



In our case, since we’re deploying a big smart contract, we’ll include 1 more additional step before confirming our smart contract deployment. We’ll be customizing the gas options of our transaction to minimize the chances of any errors caused from the gas limit being too low.



Press on the ‘Deploy’ button in Remix. In your MetaMask popup, you should see either one of the UIs in the image above; i.e. you should see either Advanced > Edit (refer to A in the image above) or Site suggested > (refer to B in the image above). Press on it and MetaMask should redirect you to the gas configurations page.

Now let’s configure our gas options. Press on ‘Edit’ and replace the fields with the values below. If your MetaMask extension displays Site suggested >, you’ll need to first press on it and then press on ‘Advanced’.
  • Max base fee - 2000
  • Priority Fee / Max priority fee - 2.5
  • Gas limit - 5000000

Once you’re done configuring the gas options, press on the ‘Confirm’ button to confirm the transaction. The contract deployment process will begin. Once the deployment is completed, the terminal in your Remix will display the transaction with an approval sign (refer to the image in ‘Expected output’). Note that this transaction might take anywhere from a few seconds to a couple of minutes to go through, depending on network conditions.

Step 14: Storing Key Information
Now let’s view the details of our contract deployment transaction. In the Remix terminal, press on the arrow beside the debug button of the transaction to expand its information. If you scroll down, you’ll be able to see the ID of our fungible token (REP). Refer to the image below.


If you’re wondering why the token ID looks so different compared to the IDs we’re used to seeing in the previous quests (e.g. 0.0.123456), that’s because the ID is returned in a Solidity address type. Solidity does not have a native way to interact with Hedera account IDs. Instead, Solidity uses the address type, which is derived from the public key associated with a Hedera account ID.

But fret not, this address functions the same as it would a typical token ID. If you copy the value of tokenAddress and search for it on a block explorer, you’ll see that you’ll be able to query for the information of the token just the same as you would for a typical token ID.

We’ll take this opportunity to introduce one of the files we created earlier in Step 9 when we were setting up our local project directory: store-information.txt. The purpose of this file is to store important pieces of information that we’ll be using in Quest 9. As mentioned, we’ll be deploying the backend of our project in this quest and we’ll be using our deployed infrastructure in Quest 9. We’ll use store-information.txt to ensure that key pieces of information are saved.

Open up store-information.txt and paste in the text below:

smart contract address: fungible token address: NFT address: topic id:

As you can infer, we’ll be using this file to store four pieces of information. We’ll be filling up two of four pieces of information in this step.

The fungible token address refers to the tokenAddress in the transaction details (refer to image at the beginning of this step). Copy its value and paste it besides fungible token address in store-information.txt.



Next, copy the address of your deployed smart contract. You can get this by pressing on the copy icon (refer to image above). Then, paste it besides smart contract address in store-information.txt.

Step 17: Creating a Topic
If you look at store-information.txt, you’ll see that we have most of the information we need already, all that’s left is to create a Topic and get its Topic ID. We’ll be using the Hashgraph JS SDK to create the Topic, similar to what we did in Quest 7.
First, open up your .env file in quest-8-backend. Copy the code below and paste it into the file.

// merchant MERCHANT_PRIVATE_KEY = replace-with-ED25519-private-key MERCHANT_ACCOUNT_ID = replace-with-ED25519-account-id

Then, open up your Hedera Developer Portal and grab the values of the ED25519 DER Encoded Private Key and ED25519 Account ID and replace the values in .env accordingly. It should look like the image below when you’re done.



After that’s done, open up your create-topic.js file and paste in the code below.

const { Client, AccountId, PrivateKey, TopicCreateTransaction, TopicMessageSubmitTransaction } = require("@hashgraph/sdk"); require("dotenv").config(); const operatorId = AccountId.fromString(process.env.MERCHANT_ACCOUNT_ID); const operatorKey = PrivateKey.fromString(process.env.MERCHANT_PRIVATE_KEY); const client = Client.forTestnet().setOperator(operatorId, operatorKey); async function createTopic() {  const createTopicTransactionResponse = await new TopicCreateTransaction().execute(client);  // Get the receipt of our transaction, to see if it was successful  const createTopicReceipt = await createTopicTransactionResponse.getReceipt(client);  // If it was successful, it will contain a new topic ID  const newTopicId = createTopicReceipt.topicId;  console.log("Our topic: " + newTopicId);  client.close(); } createTopic();

Essentially, all we’re doing is grabbing the merchant’s account ID and private key from our .env file and establishing a client connection with it. 

Then, we use the TopicCreateTransaction API to create a new topic. After that, we retrieve the topic creation receipt to obtain the topic ID.

Now let’s run the script to generate our topic - run the command below in your terminal to do so.

node create-topic.js

After doing so, you should get an output in your terminal similar to the image below.



Copy the topic ID and paste it besides topic id in store-information.txt. At this point, your store-information.txt file should look like the image in ‘Expected output’.﻿
Expected output
